text: I think the way to evaluate healing practices is to just assume the practicioner is trying to put an end to your life and thinking how good his means of doing it are. Regular pharmaceutical medicine, the doctor has all the powerful chemical drugs, you're pretty much just screwed.

In herbalism type stuff, they're working with less concentrated substances, maybe you have a chance of surviving if you're not too sick already. Chiropractic seems safe, unless the guy doing it is jacked, in which case he can just decapitate you. Massage therapy is maybe the best

Basically if you're ever sick, you're Indiana Jones and the doctor is one of your enemies undercover trying to assassinate you. Balneology, unless he figures out a way to drown you in a bathtub, you can make it through. Surgery means zero chance of escape unless a miracle occurs.

I think putting magnets on refrigerators is a wonderful cultural phenomenon. Everyone just decided to start putting small colorful images from places they've travelled to on the container where they store their food. It's something a caveman would've also come up with.
It's as if everyone decided to start putting garlands on their computer monitors
